      "source": "https://brucebolt.us/blogs/news/how-to-increase-golf-swing-speed",
      "speed_mentioned": null,
      "priority": "HIGH"
    },
    {
      "id": "SPD-009",
      "quote": "This runs counter to traditional instruction but recognizes a critical truth: it's easier to add control to a fast swing than to add speed to a controlled one.",
      "bucket": "LEARNING_AND_IMPROVEMENT",
      "physical_tag": "speed_training",
      "emotional_tags": ["paradigm_shift", "insight"],
      "source": "https://brucebolt.us/blogs/news/how-to-increase-golf-swing-speed",
      "speed_mentioned": null,
      "priority": "HIGH"
    },
    {
      "id": "SPD-010",
      "quote": "Many golfers believe a bigger swing automatically creates more speed. Harrington busts this myth by suggesting players 'think more Jon Rahm than John Daly.'",
      "bucket": "LEARNING_AND_IMPROVEMENT",
      "physical_tag": "speed_training",
      "emotional_tags": ["myth_busting", "efficiency_focus"],
      "source": "https://brucebolt.us/blogs/news/how-to-increase-golf-swing-speed",
      "speed_mentioned": null,
      "priority": "HIGH"
    },
    {
      "id": "SPD-011",
      "quote": "Rahm, despite having a relatively short backswing, generates tremendous club head speed through efficiency and proper sequencing. Shorter, more efficient swings can provide just as much power as longer ones, with better control.",
